    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>The Michigan Association for Media in Education (MAME) came into being on January 1, 1974, when two earlier organizations merged for the potential power and influence of greater numbers. The two predecessors, the Michigan Association of School Librarians (MASL) and the Michigan Audio-Visual Association (MAVA) built on such traditions as joint conferences, newsletters, and committees in establishing the new organization.</p>
      <p>Mrs. Lois T. Place, Director of School Libraries of the Detroit Public Schools, was the guiding spirit behind MASL, organizing a small group of librarians who met in November of 1949. Additional planning meetings, with growing numbers of participants, were held in the spring of 1950, and the first meeting of the Steering Committee occurred on July 12 of that year. The constitution of the new organization, with a charter membership of sixty-five, was ratified at the November 3-4, 1950 Charter Meeting, held at Haven Hill Lodge in Milford, Michigan. In addition to providing school librarians with an opportunity to share problems and ideas, the new organization was aimed at promoting better understanding among school librarians, administrators, teachers and students.</p>
      <p>According to its constitution, dated December 1, 1950, the Michigan Audio-Visual Association, with a charter membership of forty, was established to "advance education through the more efficient selection, utilization, evaluation, and administration of the audio-visual materials of instruction."</p>
      <p>A Merger Exploration Committee sent a study questionnaire to MASL and MAVA members in early 1972, and reported favorable results at the Spring Combined Conference. A Constitutional Revision Committee was appointed shortly thereafter, and overwhelming approval of the results of their efforts was announced at the 1973 Combined Conference. On December 31, 1973, both MASL and MAVA ceased to exist. On January 1, 1974, MAME, a new educational media organization with a membership soon to surpass 1,000, was born.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The record group is divided into four series: Michigan Association of School Librarians (MASL); Michigan Audio-Visual Association (MASL); MASL-MAVA combined activities; and Michigan Association for Media in Education.</p>
    </scopecontent>
